hood. He places the emotional and moral damage of each individual killer within a larger scientific framework of social, psychological, anthropological, and biological research on human development. By linking individual cases to broad social and cultural issues and illustrating the social toxicity and unresolved trauma that drive some people to kill, Dr. Garbarino highlights the humanity we share with killers and the role of understanding and empathy in breaking the cycle of violence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEvidence, ExpertzUnited States. 0aMurderzUnited StatesxPsychological aspects. 0aMurdererszUnited StatesxPsychology. 0aTrials (Murder)zUnited States. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Forensic Psychology.2bisacsh  aanthropological and biological research.  aanthropologist.  abiography.  aemotional damage.  aempathy for murderers.  ahow does someone become a serial killer.  amoral damage.  amurderer interviews.  apath of a killer.  apsychological witness.  apsychologist.  apsychology.  aserial killer pathology.  aserial killers.  asocial toxicity.  atrauma.  aunresolved trauma.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028286540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095874640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520958746423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520958746/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY